Gosling says (from the article): "So if somebody gives you an object and says 'This is an image', then it is an image. It's not like a pointer to a stream, where it just casts an image."
<br />
<br />It's ironic that when Generics are involved, the JVM doesn't preserve this guarantee.  A List&lt;String&gt; might contain a couple of AbstractQueuedSynchronizers.  Though the new Java compiler will be strict about what it lets you put in, you can craft "bad" bytecode that the JVM will happily verify (in fact, just use an older version of 'javac' to produce that bytecode).
<br />
<br />Any code that uses generic type instances from an untrusted source has to be aware that ClassCastExceptions can pop up even though there are no casts in the source code.  This loophole just makes life harder for the security-conscious programmer.
<br />
