Moreover, you can use a simple custom tool to generate all the plain .NET 2.0 interfaces and events to hook nicely into databinding (Winforms or XAML, so the tool is unfortunately misnamed).
<br />
<br />Above the manual approach you showed, the tool will generate a "strong typed" event for each property changed, as well as automatically add the code to raise the specific event. i.e.:
<br />
<br />  public EventHandler LovesXamlChanged;
<br />
<br />  bool lovesXaml;
<br />
<br />  public bool LovesXaml {
<br />    get { return lovesXaml; }
<br />    set { lovesXaml = value; RaiseLovesXamlChanged(); }
<br />  }
<br />
<br />So that you don't forget to call the Raise, and also to allow a potential presenter for the view to react to a specific event, instead of doing a potentially big switch over the changed property name as a string. (very nice if you refactor the code)
<br />
<br />More info at http://www.clariusconsulting.net/blogs/kzu/archive/2007/09/27/33235.aspx
