<br />The converter could check the age (the second parameter) and return an appropriate DataTemplate by calling FindResource on the ContentControl (the first parameter).

Actually, it's quite possible, although ugly.
<br />
<br />It is stated in the comments that the selector will not fire. That is obviously caused by the fact the content is not bound to the desired property, but to the object as a whole. 
<br />Changing this will do the trick.
<br />
<br />    &lt;ContentControl Name="cc" ContentTemplateSelector="{StaticResource SelectTheContent}" Content="{Binding Age}"&gt;
<br />      &lt;ContentControl.DataContext&gt;
<br />        &lt;l:Person Name='Ruurd Boeke' Age='29' /&gt;
<br />      &lt;/ContentControl.DataContext&gt;
<br />    &lt;/ContentControl&gt;
<br />
<br />As you can see, the content is bound to the property 'age' and thus the contenttemplateSelector will fire when it changes..
<br />The Datacontext of the contentcontrol is set to the entire object. Now, the trick is to set the datacontext of your datatemplates to that:
<br />
<br />    &lt;DataTemplate x:Key="alphaGeek" DataType="{x:Type l:Person}"&gt;
<br />      &lt;StackPanel DataContext="{Binding ElementName=cc, Path=DataContext}" Orientation="Vertical" Background="Red"&gt;
<br />        &lt;Label&gt;GEEK&lt;/Label&gt;
<br />        &lt;TextBlock Text="{Binding Name}"/&gt;
<br />      &lt;/StackPanel&gt;
<br />    &lt;/DataTemplate&gt;
<br />
<br />This will work. ;-)
<br />
<br />Complete sample:
<br />
<br />  &lt;Window.Resources&gt;
<br />    
<br />    &lt;DataTemplate x:Key="alphaGeek" DataType="{x:Type l:Person}"&gt;
<br />      &lt;StackPanel DataContext="{Binding ElementName=cc, Path=DataContext}" Orientation="Vertical" Background="Red"&gt;
<br />        &lt;Label&gt;GEEK&lt;/Label&gt;
<br />        &lt;TextBlock Text="{Binding Name}"/&gt;
<br />      &lt;/StackPanel&gt;
<br />    &lt;/DataTemplate&gt;
<br />
<br />    &lt;DataTemplate x:Key="nonGeek" DataType="{x:Type l:Person}"&gt;
<br />      &lt;StackPanel DataContext="{Binding ElementName=cc, Path=DataContext}" Orientation="Vertical" Background="Yellow"&gt;
<br />        &lt;Label&gt;nonGeek&lt;/Label&gt;
<br />        &lt;TextBlock Text="{Binding Name}"/&gt;
<br />      &lt;/StackPanel&gt;
<br />    &lt;/DataTemplate&gt;
<br />
<br />    &lt;l:GeekSelector x:Key="SelectTheContent"  NonGeekTemplate="{StaticResource nonGeek}" GeekTemplate="{StaticResource alphaGeek}" /&gt;
<br />    
<br />  &lt;/Window.Resources&gt;
<br />
<br />  &lt;StackPanel&gt;
<br />    &lt;ContentControl Name="cc" ContentTemplateSelector="{StaticResource SelectTheContent}" Content="{Binding Age}"&gt;
<br />      &lt;ContentControl.DataContext&gt;
<br />        &lt;l:Person Name='Ruurd Boeke' Age='29' /&gt;
<br />      &lt;/ContentControl.DataContext&gt;
<br />    &lt;/ContentControl&gt;
<br />
<br />    &lt;Button Click='changeAge'&gt;Toggle birthday&lt;/Button&gt;
<br />
<br />  &lt;/StackPanel&gt;
<br />&lt;/Window&gt;
<br />
<br />-------------
<br />
<br />it is not code to be proud of, but it does achieve what you wish for.

